Practice 1

  • Is \(X\) continuous or discrete?
## We can tell that X is continuous because it is defined
## for every value between some interval [a, b]. In this
## case, a=67 and b=366.
  • Compute \(P(X < 181)\)
## Probability is given by the area under a PDF. Thus, this
## probability is given by the area under the PDF for which
## x < 181. We can see that this area is composed of two
## rectangles. Further we know that the area of a rectangle
## is the product of the width and the height.
width_r1 <- 158 - 67
height_r1 <- 0.005

width_r2 <- 181 - 158
height_r2 <- 0.0016

p <- width_r1*height_r1 + width_r2*height_r2
  • Compute \(P(X > 181)\)
## Same logic as previous problem
width_r1 <- 271 - 181
height_r1 <- 0.0022

width_r2 <- 366 - 271
height_r2 <- 0.0033

p <- width_r1*height_r1 + width_r2*height_r2
  • Compute \(P(67 \leq X < 181)\)
## Same logic as previous problem
width_r1 <- 158 - 67
height_r1 <- 0.005

width_r2 <- 181 - 158
height_r2 <- 0.0016

p <- width_r1*height_r1 + width_r2*height_r2
  • Find \(x\) such that \(P(X < x) = 0.05\)
## First, we ask if the x we are interested in finding can
## be greater than 158. That is, we ask if we are looking
## for an x value that resides with the left most rectangle.
## To do this, we need to find the area in this rectangle.
## If it is greater than 0.05 then we know the x we are
## looking for must be less than 158 and somewhere in this
## rectangle.
A_left_rect = (158 - 67) * (0.005)
A_left_rect
## [1] 0.455

## Since A_left_rect > 0.05, we know the x we are looking
## for is less than 158.

## We next carry on by looking for the width of the
## rectangle starting at x=67 and extending in the positive
## direction up to x such that the area of the rectangle it
## produces is 0.05.

## Another way of saying all that is as follows:

## We know the smallest value x that X can produce is 67. We
## also know that up to x=158, the height of the pdf is
## 0.005. Since area under the pdf is probability, and area
## is also width times height, we can do a little algebra to
## solve for width:
## p = w x h
## w = p / h
w <- 0.05 / 0.005
x <- 67 + w
  • Find \(x\) such that \(P(X > x) = 0.05\)
## Same logic as above but this time we come in from the
## right side.
## p = w x h
## w = p / h
w <- 0.05 / 0.0033
x <- 366 - w

Practice 2

  • Is \(X\) continuous or discrete?
## X is discrete because it is defined for only a few
## individual x values.
  • Compute \(P(X < 70)\)
## Given a probability mass function, probabilities of a
## particular outcome are given by the height of the pmf at
## that value. The x values 51 and 40 are the only x values
## that satisfy X<73
p <- 0.5517 + 0.0776
  • Compute \(P(X > 70)\)
## Same logic as above
p <- 0.1724
  • Compute \(P(40 \leq X < 70)\)
## Same logic as above
p <- 0.5517 + 0.0776
  • Compute the mean and variance of \(X\)
mux <- 0.5517*40 + 0.0776*51 + 0.1983*70 + 0.1724*78

# option 1
varx <- 0.5517*( 40 - mux )^2 + 
         0.0776*( 51 - mux )^2 + 
         0.1983*( 70 - mux )^2 + 
         0.1724*( 78 - mux)^2

# option 2
varx <- 0.5517*40^2 + 
        0.0776*51^2 + 
        0.1983*70^2 + 
        0.1724*78^2 -
        mux^2

Practice 1

For the random variable \(X \sim N(\mu_X=10, \sigma_X=2)\)

## Begin by defining the parameters of the Normal
## distribution that we are being asked about.
mux <- 10
sigx <- 2
  • Compute \(P(X < 12)\)
## Recall that for continuous distributions P(X<x) =
## P(X<=x), which keeps our use of `lower.tail` pretty
## straight forward.
pnorm(12, mux, sigx, lower.tail=TRUE)
## [1] 0.8413447
  • Compute \(P(X > 8)\)
pnorm(8, mux, sigx, lower.tail=FALSE)
## [1] 0.8413447
  • Compute \(P(8 \leq X < 12)\)
pnorm(12, mux, sigx, lower.tail=TRUE) - pnorm(8, mux, sigx, lower.tail=TRUE)
## [1] 0.6826895

Practice 2

For the random variable \(X \sim \mathcal{Poisson}(\lambda=4)\)

## You may not have seen a Poisson random variable before,
## regardless of whether you have or haven't, R knows about
## it and provides all the usual functions to work with it:
## dpois
## ppois
## qpois
## rpois

## Also, since you may not have seen a Pisson distribution,
## I have included code to plot it for you, so you can
## corroborate the results you obtain using the above functions
## with what you can obtain from a visual.
  • Find \(x\) such that \(P(X \leq x) = 0.5\)
## Reading off this graph, we see that P(X<=x)=0.05 occurs
## at x=4
p <- seq(0,0.99,0.01)
qf <- qpois(p, 4, lower.tail=TRUE)
d <- data.table(p, qf)
ggplot(d, aes(x=p, y=qf)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks=qf) +
  xlab('P(X <= x)') +
  ylab('x') +
  geom_vline(xintercept=0.5, linetype=2)


# same result from the straight forward use of the qpois
# function
qpois(0.5, 4, lower.tail=TRUE)
## [1] 4
  • Find \(x\) such that \(P(X < x) = 0.05\)
## Here, you have to be careful to remember that P(X<=x) is
## not the same as P(X<x) when X is discrete. 
p <- seq(0,0.99,0.01)
qf <- qpois(p, 4, lower.tail=TRUE)
d <- data.table(p, qf)
ggplot(d, aes(x=p, y=qf)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks=qf) +
  xlab('P(X <= x)') +
  ylab('x') +
  geom_vline(xintercept=0.05, linetype=2)


## The +1 is because `lower.tail=TRUE` gives P(X<=x) but we
## are asked for P(X < x). Here, we are using this fact:
## P(X<=x) = P(X<x+1) if x can only be 1, 2, 3, 4... n
qpois(0.05, 4, lower.tail=TRUE) + 1
## [1] 2
  • Find \(x\) such that \(P(X > x) = 0.05\)
## Nothing to be extra careful about here becuase
## `lower.tail=FALSE` will give us x such that P(X>x)
p <- seq(0,0.99,0.01)
qf <- qpois(p, 4, lower.tail=FALSE)
d <- data.table(p, qf)
ggplot(d, aes(x=p, y=qf)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks=qf) +
  xlab('P(X > x)') +
  ylab('x') +
  geom_vline(xintercept=0.05, linetype=2)


qpois(0.05, 4, lower.tail=FALSE)
## [1] 8

NHST

Practice 1

Consider an experiment in which participants first learn novel categories, and are subsequently asked to perform some other task. The question the researchers are interested in is how initial learning affects the subsequent task, and it is therefore critical that participants that didn’t learn anything be excluded from the final analysis. An exclusion criteria is set such that any participant that fails to reach at least \(60\%\) accuracy by the end of training is excluded. Suppose that data is collected from 30 participants, and of these, 5 are excluded. Is this greater than would be expected if the true probability – denoted \(p\) – of meeting the exclusion criteria was 0.1?

  • Answer this question going through all 5 steps in long form.
## 1
## Let X = number excluded
## X ~ Binomial(n, p)

## H0: p = 0.1
## H1: p > 0.1

## 2
# alpha = 0.05

## 3
## p_hat = n_success / n_total
## p_hat ~ Binomial(n, p); x -> x/n_total 
## "x/n_total" is to convert between count and proportion

## 4
n <- 30
p_hat_obs <- 5 / n

## 5
p_val <- pbinom(p_hat_obs*n-1, n, 0.1, lower.tail=FALSE)
p_hat_crit <- qbinom(0.05, n, 0.1, lower.tail=FALSE)/n

p_val
## [1] 0.1754949
p_hat_crit
## [1] 0.2

x <- 0:n
fx <- dbinom(x, n, 0.1)
x <- x / n
d <- data.table(x, fx)
ggplot(d, aes(x, fx)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_segment(aes(x=p_hat_obs,  
                   xend=p_hat_obs,  
                   y=0,  
                   yend=max(fx)),
               linetype=2, 
               colour='grey') +
  geom_segment(aes(x=p_hat_crit,  
                   xend=p_hat_crit,  
                   y=0,  
                   yend=max(fx)),
               linetype=2, 
               colour='red')


if(p_val < 0.05) {
  print('reject H0')
} else {
  print('fail to reject H0')
}
## [1] "fail to reject H0"

if(p_hat_obs > p_hat_crit) {
  print('reject H0')
} else {
  print('fail to reject H0')
}
## [1] "fail to reject H0"

## NOTE: I haven't shown how to compute confidence interval
## estimates from Binomial random variables (or any discrete
## random variable for that matter). It follows the same
## principles in most ways as our approach for continuous
## random variables, but it turns out to be a bit more
## involved. Because of that, I will not expect the CI
## intervals that you compute by hand to exactly match those
## from R. You will, however, need to be careful to properly
## deal with lower.tail=F issues.
  • Is there a built in function you can use? If so, use it.
binom.test(p_hat_obs*n, n=n, p=0.1, alternative='greater', conf.level=0.95)
## 
##  Exact binomial test
## 
## data:  p_hat_obs * n and n
## number of successes = 5, number of trials = 30, p-value = 0.1755
## alternative hypothesis: true probability of success is greater than 0.1
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.06805557 1.00000000
## sample estimates:
## probability of success 
##              0.1666667
  • Report a point estimates for \(\hat{p}\)
p_hat_obs
## [1] 0.1666667
  • Report the critical value for \(\alpha=0.05\)
x <- 0:n
fx <- pbinom(x, n, 0.1, lower.tail=FALSE)
x <- x/n
d <- data.table(x, fx)
ggplot(d, aes(x, fx)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_hline(yintercept=0.05) +
  geom_segment(aes(x=x, xend=x+1/n, y=fx, yend=fx)) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=round(x, 1)) +
  ylab('P(X > x)') +
  xlab('x')


p_hat_crit
## [1] 0.2
  • Compute power against the alternative \(H_1\) that \(p\) is .3
x <- 0:30
pmf_h0 <- dbinom(x, n, 0.1)
pmf_h1 <- dbinom(x, n, 0.3)
x <- x/n
d <- data.table(x, pmf_h0, pmf_h1)
dd <- melt(d, 
          id.vars='x', 
          measure.vars=c('pmf_h0', 'pmf_h1'),
          variable.name='h',
          value.name='fx')
ggplot(dd) +
  geom_point(aes(x, fx, colour=h)) +
  geom_vline(xintercept=p_hat_crit, linetype=2)


## power is the probability in the rejection region
type_I <- d[x > p_hat_crit, sum(pmf_h0)]
type_II <- d[x <= p_hat_crit, sum(pmf_h1)]
power <- d[x > p_hat_crit, sum(pmf_h1)]

Practice 2

Consider an experiment in which participants study a list of words and are subsequently asked to recall as many of the studied words as possible. Suppose that data is collected from 10 participants and the percentage of words recalled by each participant is given by

\[\begin{equation} x = ( 0.56, 0.56, 0.54, 0.64, 0.47, 0.67, 0.41, 0.57, 0.66, 0.62 ) \end{equation}\]

Let \(X\) be the random variable that each participants performance is drawn from, and suppose we know \(\sigma_x = 0.15\).

Is \(\mu_x\) significantly greater than \(0.6\)?

## 1
## H0: mux = .6
## H1: mux > .6

## 2
# alpha <- 0.05

## 3
## mu_x_hat = xbar 
## x_bar ~ N(mu_x_bar, sig_x_bar)
## mu_x_bar = mu_x
## sig_x_bar = sig_x/sqrt(n)

n <- length(x)
sig_x <- 0.15
mu_x_bar <- 0.60
sig_x_bar <- sig_x/sqrt(n)

## 4
x_bar_obs <- mean(x)

## 5
p_val <- pnorm(x_bar_obs, mu_x_bar, sig_x_bar, lower.tail=FALSE)
x_bar_crit <- qnorm(0.05, mu_x_bar, sig_x_bar, lower.tail=FALSE)
  • Is there a built-in function you can use? If so, use it.
## Unfortunately, there is not.
  • Report point and interval estimates for \(\hat{\mu_x}\)
# point estimate
x_bar_obs
## [1] 0.5676709

# interval estimate (90% interval)
ci_width <- qnorm(0.95, mu_x_bar, sig_x_bar) - qnorm(0.05, mu_x_bar, sig_x_bar)
ci_lower <- x_bar_obs - ci_width / 2
ci_upper <- x_bar_obs + ci_width / 2


# interval estimate (95% interval)
ci_width <- qnorm(0.975, mu_x_bar, sig_x_bar) - qnorm(0.025, mu_x_bar, sig_x_bar)
ci_lower <- x_bar_obs - ci_width / 2
ci_upper <- x_bar_obs + ci_width / 2
  • Report the critical value for \(\alpha=0.05\)
x_bar_crit
## [1] 0.6780223
  • Compute power against the alternative \(H_1\) that \(\mu_x\) is 0.62
x <- seq(mu_x_bar-sig_x_bar*4, mu_x_bar+sig_x_bar*4, 0.001)
pdf_h0 <- dnorm(x, 0.60, sig_x_bar)
pdf_h1 <- dnorm(x, 0.62, sig_x_bar)
d <- data.table(x, pdf_h0, pdf_h1)
dd <- melt(d, 
          id.vars='x', 
          measure.vars=c('pdf_h0', 'pdf_h1'),
          variable.name='h',
          value.name='fx')
ggplot(dd) +
  geom_line(aes(x, fx, colour=h)) +
  geom_vline(xintercept=x_bar_crit, linetype=2)


typeI <- pnorm(x_bar_crit, 0.60, sig_x_bar, lower.tail=FALSE)
typeII <- pnorm(x_bar_crit, 0.62, sig_x_bar, lower.tail=TRUE)
power <- pnorm(x_bar_crit, 0.62, sig_x_bar, lower.tail=FALSE)

Practice 3

Consider an experiment in which participants attempt to toss a ping pong ball as accurately as possible to a target. Suppose that data is collected from 15 participants and that the mean reach error per participant is given by

\[\begin{equation} x = ( 12.06, -0.86, 7.55, 16.29, -10.36, -19.27, 0.7, -3.54, -8.14, -6.5, -9.74, 10.9, 17.28, 14.88, -6.44 ) \end{equation}\]

Let \(X\) be the random variable that each participant’s performance is drawn from.

Is \(\mu_x\) significantly different from \(0\)?

## 1
## H0: mux = 0
## H1: mux != 0

## 2
# alpha <- 0.05

## 3
## mu_x_hat = x_bar ~ N(mu_x_bar, sig_x_bar)
## mu_x_bar = mu_x
## sig_x_bar = sig_x / sqrt(n)
## Don't know sig_x so we need to estimate it
## This means we need to transform everything for a t-test
## t_x_bar = (x_bar - mu_x_bar) / sig_x_bar 
## t_x_bar ~ t(n-1)

n <- length(x)
df <- n - 1
mu_x_bar <- 0

sig_x <- sd(x)
sig_x_bar <- sig_x/sqrt(n)

## 4
x_bar_obs <- mean(x)
t_obs <- (x_bar_obs - mu_x_bar) / sig_x_bar

## 5
p_val_lower <- pt(-abs(t_obs), n-1, lower.tail = TRUE)
p_val_upper <- pt(abs(t_obs), n-1, lower.tail = FALSE)
p_val <- p_val_lower + p_val_upper

t_crit_lower <- qt(0.025, n-1)
t_crit_upper <- qt(0.975, n-1)
  • Is there a built in function you can use? If so, use it.
t.test(x, mu=0, alternative='two.sided')
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  x
## t = 0.33459, df = 14, p-value = 0.7429
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -5.342954  7.318086
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##  0.987566
  • Report point and interval estimates for \(\hat{\mu_x}\)
# The insight you have to have here is that to convert
# between t which has mean 0 and (approximately) sd 1, you
# have to scale the interval you get from the t by sig_x_bar.
ci_width <- ( t_crit_upper - t_crit_lower) * sig_x_bar
ci_lower <- x_bar_obs - ci_width / 2
ci_upper <- x_bar_obs + ci_width / 2

# print out stuff to compare with t.test()
p_val
## [1] 0.7428955
ci_lower
## [1] -5.342954
ci_upper
## [1] 7.318086
  • Report the critical values for \(\alpha=0.05\)
t_crit_lower
## [1] -2.144787
t_crit_upper
## [1] 2.144787
  • Compute power against the alternative \(H_1\) that \(\mu_x\) is 2 assuming that the population standard deviation is equal to the sample standard deviation.
# In x_bar units the mean of the null and the alternative
# are 2 units apart. However, since we have to estimate the
# population standard deviation from the data, we need to
# work with t-distributions.
# mu_h0 = 0 --> t
# mu_h1 = 2 --> t + 2/sig_x_bar
lower_t <- -4
upper_t <-  4 + 2/sig_x_bar
t <- seq(lower_t, upper_t, 0.1)
pdf_h0 <- dt(t, n-1)
pdf_h1 <- dt(t-2/sig_x_bar, n-1)
d <- data.table(t, pdf_h0, pdf_h1)
dd <- melt(d, 
          id.vars='t', 
          measure.vars=c('pdf_h0', 'pdf_h1'),
          variable.name='h',
          value.name='ft')
ggplot(dd) +
  geom_line(aes(t, ft, colour=h)) +
  geom_vline(xintercept=t_crit_lower, linetype=2) +
  geom_vline(xintercept=t_crit_upper, linetype=2)


# contribution from upper tail
typeI_upper <- pt(t_crit_upper, n-1, lower.tail=FALSE)
typeII_upper <- pt(t_crit_upper-2/sig_x_bar, n-1, lower.tail=TRUE)
power_upper <- pt(t_crit_upper-2/sig_x_bar, n-1, lower.tail=FALSE)

# contribution from lower tail
typeI_lower <- pt(t_crit_lower, n-1, lower.tail=TRUE)
typeII_lower <- pt(t_crit_lower-2/sig_x_bar, n-1, lower.tail=FALSE)
power_lower <- pt(t_crit_lower-2/sig_x_bar, n-1, lower.tail=TRUE)

# sum together to get total
typeI <- typeI_upper + typeI_lower
typeII <- typeII_upper + typeII_lower
typeI <- power_upper + power_lower

Data Wrangling

Consider an experiment in which a set of rats run through a set of mazes some number of times each. The researchers running this experiment are interested in how quickly rats can run these mazes, and so they plan to record the time in seconds each rat takes to complete each run of each maze. Before investing time and resources into a full experiment, two graduate students are tasked with running a scaled-down version (i.e., pilot experiments) to make sure everything is set up correctly.

  • Graduate student 1 acquired the following data:

https://crossley.github.io/cogs2020/data/maze/d_wide.csv

  • Graduate student 2 acquired the following data:

https://crossley.github.io/cogs2020/data/maze/d_long.csv

  • After validating the pilot data, they ran a full experiment and acquired the following data:

https://crossley.github.io/cogs2020/data/maze/maze.csv

Practice 3

  • Recreate the following visualisation of their results. Note that error bars represent standard error of the mean (SEM). Also note that to get SEM here, first compute the mean time per maze per rat. Then, compute the mean and standard error from these values.
d <- fread('https://crossley.github.io/cogs2020/data/maze/maze.csv')
dd <- d[, mean(time), .(rat, maze)]
ddd <- dd[, .(mean(V1), sd(V1)/sqrt(length(unique(rat)))), .(maze)]
ggplot(ddd, aes(maze, V1)) +
  geom_pointrange(aes(ymin=V1-V2, ymax=V1+V2)) +
  xlab('maze') +
  ylab('mean maze time')
